    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-03-11T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-03-11T04:00:00-05:00" n="36"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d36">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8532: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-03-11T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 11, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 11—6:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>89. Reference paragraph 1 Embassy’s 54, February 8, 5 p.m. and subsequent
                    telegrams.</p>
                <pb facs="0046" n="39" xml:id="pg_39"/>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Sung Che Yuan returned March 9 to Peiping from Tientsin. The subject of
                        his conversations with Japanese while there is still a matter of
                        speculation.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Sung is reported to have said in an interview granted March 10 to Chinese
                        pressmen that he would continue to follow his policy of supporting the
                        National Government, that the development of economic resources would be
                        guided by the principles of environments, reciprocity, and mutual
                        prosperity, that mines would be developed first and then railways, and that
                        he would continue to oppose communism.</item>
                </list>
                <p>By mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
